\begin_layout Subsection*
1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The contract curve connects all points which are a Pareto efficient equilibrium.
 At each point on it, the indifference curves of each agent are tangent
 to each other.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The slope of agent A indifference curve is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\frac{\partial u_{A}(x,y)}{\partial x}}{\frac{\partial u_{A}(x,y)}{\partial y}}=\frac{\frac{\alpha_{1}}{x}}{\alpha_{2}}=\frac{\alpha_{1}}{\alpha_{2}x}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly, for agent B:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\frac{\partial u_{B}(x,y)}{\partial x}}{\frac{\partial u_{B}(x,y)}{\partial y}}=\frac{\frac{\beta_{1}}{x}}{\beta_{2}}=\frac{\beta_{1}}{\beta_{2}x}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equating the above:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\alpha_{1}}{\alpha_{2}x_{A}}=\frac{\beta_{1}}{\beta_{2}x_{B}}\Rightarrow\frac{x_{A}}{x_{B}}=\frac{\alpha_{1}\beta_{2}}{\alpha_{2}\beta_{1}}
\]

\end_inset

Using 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{A}+x_{B}=C$
\end_inset

 and substituting we conclude:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{cases}
x_{A}= & \frac{\alpha_{1}\beta_{2}}{\alpha_{1}\beta_{2}+\alpha_{2}\beta_{1}}C\\
x_{B}= & \frac{\alpha_{2}\beta_{1}}{\alpha_{1}\beta_{2}+\alpha_{2}\beta_{1}}C
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which is basically another way of telling that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{A}=\gamma C$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{B}=(1-\gamma)C$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\gamma\leq1$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the contract curve yields a 
\series bold
vertical segment 
\series default
that connects 
\begin_inset Formula $(\frac{\alpha_{1}\beta_{2}}{\alpha_{1}\beta_{2}+\alpha_{2}\beta_{1}}C,0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(\frac{\alpha_{1}\beta_{2}}{\alpha_{1}\beta_{2}+\alpha_{2}\beta_{1}}C,D)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to that, the segments that connect 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,0)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $(\frac{\alpha_{1}\beta_{2}}{\alpha_{1}\beta_{2}+\alpha_{2}\beta_{1}}C,0$
\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $(\frac{\alpha_{1}\beta_{2}}{\alpha_{1}\beta_{2}+\alpha_{2}\beta_{1}}C,D$
\end_inset

) with 
\begin_inset Formula $(C,D)$
\end_inset

 belong to the contract curve as well.
 It can be explained by the fact that each point on these segments is an
 equilibrium which cannot be optimized anymore (improvement could have only
 be done by moving outside the Edgeworth box, which is obviously impossible).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The vertical segment can be explained intuitively by the fact the the slope
 of the indifference curve of each agent does not depend on the value of
 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 at all.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The marginal utility for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is decreasing for each agent, with the marginal utility for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 being fixed.
 Reducing agent A allocation from 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\alpha_{1}\beta_{2}}{\alpha_{1}\beta_{2}+\alpha_{2}\beta_{1}}C$
\end_inset

 to a lower value would bring him to a point where his marginal utility
 from 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 relative to 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is higher than that of agent 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, which requires allocating 
\series bold
all
\series default
 the available 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 to agent B, and vice versa.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
3.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The initial endowments for the agents are 
\begin_inset Formula $pC$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-p)D$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 The demanded quantity by agent A is the point on the budget line where
 the slope equals to the indifference curve slope:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\alpha_{1}}{\alpha_{2}x_{A}}=\frac{p}{1-p}\Rightarrow x_{A}=\frac{\alpha_{1}(1-p)}{\alpha_{2}p};\,\,y_{A}=\frac{pC}{1-p}-\frac{\alpha_{1}}{\alpha_{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly for agent B it is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{\beta_{1}(1-p)}{\beta_{2}p},\frac{pD}{1-p}-\frac{\beta_{1}}{\beta_{2}}\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Adding up to get 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{A}+x_{B}=C$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\alpha_{1}(1-p)}{\alpha_{2}p}+\frac{\beta_{1}(1-p)}{\beta_{2}p}=C
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1-p}{p}\left(\frac{\alpha_{1}}{\alpha_{2}}+\frac{\beta_{1}}{\beta_{2}}\right)=C\Rightarrow\frac{1}{p}=\frac{C}{\frac{\alpha_{1}}{\alpha_{2}}+\frac{\beta_{1}}{\beta_{2}}}+1=\frac{\alpha_{2}\beta_{2}C+\alpha_{1}\beta_{2}+\beta_{1}\alpha_{2}}{\alpha_{1}\beta_{2}+\beta_{1}\alpha_{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And finally:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p=\frac{\alpha_{1}\beta_{2}+\beta_{1}\alpha_{2}}{\alpha_{2}\beta_{2}C+\alpha_{1}\beta_{2}+\beta_{1}\alpha_{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1-p=\frac{\alpha_{2}\beta_{2}C}{\alpha_{2}\beta_{2}C+\alpha_{1}\beta_{2}+\beta_{1}\alpha_{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An interesting observation is that 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is not part of the price at all - which makes sense, as the amount of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 has no impact on the marginal utility of each agent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
4.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equilibrium allocation is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{A}=\frac{\alpha_{1}(1-p)}{\alpha_{2}p}=\frac{\alpha_{1}\alpha_{2}\beta_{2}C}{\alpha_{2}(\alpha_{1}\beta_{2}+\beta_{1}\alpha_{2})}=\frac{\alpha_{1}\beta_{2}}{\alpha_{1}\beta_{2}+\alpha_{2}\beta_{1}}C
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{A}=\frac{pC}{1-p}-\frac{\alpha_{1}}{\alpha_{2}}=\frac{(\alpha_{1}\beta_{2}+\beta_{1}\alpha_{2})C}{\alpha_{2}\beta_{2}C}-\frac{\alpha_{1}}{\alpha_{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{B}=\frac{\beta_{1}(1-p)}{\beta_{2}p}=\frac{\beta_{1}\alpha_{2}\beta_{2}C}{\beta_{2}(\alpha_{1}\beta_{2}+\beta_{1}\alpha_{2})}=\frac{\beta_{1}\alpha_{2}C}{\alpha_{1}\beta_{2}+\beta_{1}\alpha_{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{B}=\frac{pC}{1-p}-\frac{\beta_{1}}{\beta_{2}}=\frac{(\alpha_{1}\beta_{2}+\beta_{1}\alpha_{2})C}{\alpha_{2}\beta_{2}C}-\frac{\beta_{1}}{\beta_{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which is clearly on the contract curve (
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 values match those found in part (1), and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 values doesn't matter at all).
\end_layout

