\begin_layout Subsection*
6.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The non-standard feature of this model (when applying it to financial markets)
 is having different utility functions for the different possible states.
 The common model would be:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U(x,y)=pu_{!}(x)+(1-p)u_{2}(y)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}\equiv u_{2}$
\end_inset

 being the same function, which is not the case here, as 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}(x)=\alpha_{1}log(x)$
\end_inset

 while 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}(y)=\alpha_{2}y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

